defaultQ335 default&#xa0; 
defaultChair:default Thank you very much for coming to give evidence this afternoon.
default 
defaultOne of the things we will be looking at is how procurement might be used for a number of objectives.
default 
defaultWe will begin by looking at how it might be used by local councils to tackle social disadvantage and poverty.
default 
defaultDo you think councils are actually doing this effectively?
default 
defaultAre they getting it right, or is there more they could be doing?
default 
defaultWho would like to start?
defaultMatthew Jackson:default In short, the answer is yes, in some localities.
default 
defaultIt is very much dependent upon the culture of procurement officers within particular local authorities.
default 
defaultWhere there is an effective strategic relationship between procurement and economic development, in particular within local authorities, that is where procurement leads to wider benefits.
defaultThere is effective engagement between procurement officers and economic
default-
defaultdevelopment practitioners where there is economic intelligence around the challenges of the issue—around things like 
defaultworklessness
default, low skills, poor business sustainability and those sorts of concerns, i.e. where there is a culture of achieving wider benefits through the process of procurement.
defaultOliver Henmandefault: At NCVO, we understand that local authorities are facing a challenging economic environment.
default 
defaultFunding for services is decreasing while demand is increasing.
default 
defaultThis does change the balance of what can be funded and what cannot be funded.
default 
defaultHowever, in these tough conditions, more effective procurement would enable the resources that are available to be better targeted.
default 
defaultIt is important to involve community organisations early in the process, even pre
default-
defaultprocurement, in order to identify the needs of a local area and make sure resources are best used for that area.
defaultRicharddefault defaultMacfarlanedefault: From my limited experience of the number of local authorities I meet, many are still quite unaware of it at a practical level.
default 
defaultProcurement officers often have not heard about the Public
default 
defaultServices (Social
default 
defaultValue) Act at all; it is quite new.
default 
defaultOn the other hand, quite a lot of them have been doing social value for quite a long time.
default 
defaultThey have had powers under the Localism
default 
defaultAct.
default 
defaultThe LGA, for example, put out guidance on targeted recruitment and training as a social value three or four years ago.
default 
defaultThere has been a lot of activity.
default 
defaultThe first local
default-
defaultauthority contract I did with social value in it was in 1981.
default 
defaultIt has been around and on the blocks for quite a long time.
default 
defaultThe issue is pushing it forward in the very crowded agenda that people are trying to deal with at the moment.
defaultQ336 default&#xa0; 
defaultChair:default How far is it down to whether individual procurement officers might know what is going on and understand how to do it?
default 
defaultHow far is it an issue of political leadership from councils that requires officers to recognise these objectives and pursue them?
defaultRicharddefault defaultMacfarlanedefault: Political leadership is key, because it tells officers this is a high priority on the long agenda of things they have to deal with: re
default-
defaultcontracting, cuts and changes of all sorts.
default 
defaultFor places like 
defaultBirmingham
default or Nottingham or 
defaultLiverpool
default, which are the cities I have been working in, political leadership is key to saying, “This is something we have to take forward and are going to take forward”.
default 
defaultThe officers then get their ducks in line and start to work out how to do it and where to do it and so forth.
defaultMatthew Jackson:default Some of the most effective practice is where local authorities have aligned their procurement strategies, priorities and practices with wider corporate strategy and community strategy as well.
default 
defaultTo give an example, we have done a range of pieces of work with Manchester City Council.
default 
defaultOne of the simplest things they have undertaken is to put, at the outset of each of their tender documents, what their core corporate prior
defaultities are as a local authority, 
defaultwhich are around reducing 
defaultworklessness
default, raising aspiration and private
default-
defaultsector growth.
default 
defaultThat flow of priorities and objectives flows through the entirety of the procurement process.
defaultThat is important in terms of the supply chain as well.
default 
defaultIf you are influencing the behaviour of the supply chain to think about what your core priorities are as a local authority, it can have knock
default-
defaulton consequences in terms of how they behave and what added value they deliver through procurement beyond the delivery of services.
defaultOliver Henmandefault: Furthermore, part of it is simply through a lack of awareness.
default 
defaultIn many cases, procurement officials do not necessarily know what is allowable even under the current rules.
default 
defaultCertainly, with the new rules proposed now by 
defaultBrussels
default, the new EU Procurement Directive, that lack of understanding may well be further exacerbated.
default 
defaultThere is a lot of work to be done around awareness
default-
defaultraising, highlighting to officials what is actually possible, and highlighting good examples of where more innovative procurement has been used.
defaultQ337 default&#xa0; 
defaultSimon Danczuk:default To what extent are local councils exploiting the Public Services (Social Value) Act 
default2012 in
default terms of encouraging social benefits to their communities?
defaultMatthew Jackson:default The Public Services (Social Value) Act is a continuation of many of the things local authorities were doing anyway, particularly on the capital side of procurement—more construction
default-
defaulttype services.
default 
defaultFor years, a significant emphasis has been placed upon apprenticeships, job creation, and skills and training.
default 
defaultThe Public
default 
defaultServices (Social
default 
defaultValue) Act has enabled authorities to formalise activities around wider social and economic benefits on the revenue side of things, i.e. more revenue
default-
defaultfocused services as well.
defaultRicharddefault defaultMacfarlanedefault: Perhaps the major changes in the area focus on social enterprise as a delivery route for it.
default 
defaultOn the whole, many local authorities with substantial teams of officers and so forth have already been doing it and are doing it already.
default 
defaultThe big gain from the Public
default 
defaultServices (Social
default 
defaultValue) Act would be if other Ministries and other parts of Government started to do what local authorities actually have a long track record of doing, but it has never transferred outside of that to non
default-
defaultlocal authority contracts, except perhaps to 
defaultCrossrail
default, a few transport projects in London and one or two hospital projects around the country.
defaultThere is some impact, but there is also a downside.
default 
defaultBy leaving out works contracts, where most of the activity has been out of the Public
default 
defaultServices (Social
default 
defaultValue) Act, you are actually sending a message.
default 
defaultPeople are saying, “Hang on a minute.
default 
defaultWe have been doing works projects, but we are 
defaultnot expected to do that now.”
default 
defaultBy leaving works projects out of the mix and focusing on services, there is the potential for some negative messages to go out about the works side, which has been very important.
defaultOliver Henmandefault: Not enough has been done with it so far over a year.
default 
defaultThe Public
default 
defaultServices (Social
default 
defaultValue) Act is a very useful tool, and it could be better used by local authorities.
default 
defaultAs I said before around procurement officials, the feeling we get from members is that there is still a tendency to focus on the lowest price in procurement exercises and not look at the wider social and environment wellbeing indicators.
defaultOne example is a 
defaultLondon
default charity 
defaultthat 
defaultlost its contract delivering home care and end
default-
defaultof
default-
defaultl
defaultife care for a local authority 
defaultbecause the contractor price/quality weightings shifted from being 50/50 to being 70/30 in favour of lowest price.
default 
defaultThey could not compete with other private care providers.
default 
defaultThere is a risk that procurement officials are still looking for the lowest
default-
defaultcost option.
default 
defaultAs I said at the beginning, it reflects the wider economic environment.
default 
defaultThere is something to be said for showing that this does have a long
default-
defaultterm economic benefit and that it will save money and lead to more efficient services over the long term.
defaultQ338 default&#xa0; 
defaultSimon Danczuk:default Oliver, your organisation suggests that the Public Services (Social Value) Act be amended to apply to any level of contract; is that right?
defaultOliver Henmandefault: That was a particular point we were seeking clarification on.
default 
defaultOur understanding is the Public
default 
defaultServices (Social
default 
defaultValue) Act only applies above the EU procurement thresholds, which are €200,000 and are going up to €750,000 in the new procurement rules, which would take most of the contracts that reach the voluntary sector out of the scope of the Public Services (Social Value) Act.
default 
defaultWe felt that there was perhaps a contradiction there, because the spirit of the Public
default 
defaultServices (Social
default 
defaultValue) Act should apply, ideally, across the piece, even for those smaller community
default-
defaultbased projects that many of our organisations are delivering.
defaultQ339 default&#xa0; 
defaultSimon Danczuk:default You think it should apply to every service contract.
defaultOliver Henmandefault: It would make sense for the spirit of it 
defaultto apply across the board, yes.
defaultQ340 default&#xa0; 
defaultSimon Danczuk:default Do you not think that is a lot of bureaucracy?
defaultOliver Henmandefault: The ideal way for it being applied—it is a conversation we have had previously—is around ensuring that the spirit of wider impact is taken on board.
default 
defaultIt does not necessarily require a huge amount of additional work in those contracts; it does not necessarily require a huge amount of additional questions in the contract.
default 
defaultIt is about embedding that into the core part of the contract so that this becomes the normal way of evaluating any contract: you look at price, but you also look at the social impact, and that does generate a saving.
defaultAn example might be an employment
default-
defaultrelated service, which could actually lead to savings on youth
default-
defaultcrime budgets or healthcare budgets.
default 
defaultIt does actually generate a saving, but it may come beyond the scope of that particular project.
default 
defaultIt is identifying ways that you can quantify those savings.
defaultQ341 default&#xa0; 
defaultSimon Danczuk:default Some might argue that you are arguing against lowest
default-
defaultprice contract, but why not have a laissez
default-
defaultfaire approach and let local authorities get the service delivered as cheaply as possible?
default 
defaultSome would argue there is a premium attached to trying to root out social value within the contract and the local authority has to pay more to get more out of the contract.
default 
defaultWhy not let them 
defaultgo for the cheapest price and then use the savings they make to buy additional services?
default 
defaultWhat is wrong with that argument, Richard?
defaultRicharddefault defaultMacfarlanedefault: If you specify your social benefit as part of the contract requirements—i.e. it goes into the specification—the cheapest price always has to be for the delivery of that whole specification, so you do not separate out the cost of the social value.
default 
defaultTo deliver the contract without the social value would not be meeting the contract objectives, if you follow the idea that you are including social value as part of the contract requirements.
default 
defaultHowever, the evidence from the big body of works contracts has been that these are being delivered without additional cost.
defaultFor example, the Glasgow
default 
defaultHousing
default 
defaultAssociation have delivered £2.3
default 
defaultbillion of works contracts in quite intricate housing regeneration with occupied homes—it is quite difficult stuff—and Savills have been doing annual evaluations of their cost outturns.
default 
defaultThey have delivered 60,000 person
default-
defaultweeks of work for apprentices and trainees at or below the market cost for doing the sort of work they have been doing; that has been independently assessed.
defaultThe key thing there is that it depends a bit on what the social
default-
defaultvalue requirement is.
default 
defaultFor training and employment, there is obviously other employment funding out there that contractors or clients can access.
default 
defaultThey can offset any additional costs by pulling in money from the Work
default 
defaultProgramme or Construction
default 
defaultSkills grants and so forth.
default 
defaultThere may be other types of social value: for example, requiring contractors to seek out local suppliers.
default 
defaultThey do not have to give them contracts, but going through the route of, say, going to Find
default-
defaultI
defaultt
default-
defaultI
defaultn
default-
defaultBirmingham, which is a database of Birmingham firms, and saying, “You must go and find this in Birmingham”, can actually reduce the contractor’s cost, because they find local suppliers instead of bringing them down the road from Leeds or somewhere.
defaultIt depends a lot on what it is you are specifying, what other resources are out there and what the cost impact of that is.
default 
defaultThere is evidence from works contracts on that, but not really from services.
defaultQ342 default&#xa0; 
defaultSimon Danczuk:default Matthew, you were saying there were some good examples in Manchester City Council.
default 
defaultIf it is such good practice, why are the other nine councils in Greater Manchester not doing the same thing?
defaultMatthew Jackson:default It relates to the previous question.
default 
defaultA lot of it is about measurement of impact of things like social value.
default 
defaultWe do not have a standardised approach across local authorities for measuring wider economic, social and environmental impacts.
default 
defaultAt the moment, the case will be that a service will go out to contract; an organisation will start delivering that activity, but there is no real mechanism or means of highlighting the impact of, say, an apprenticeship scheme and what impact it has on addressing issues like unemployment within a particular locality.
default 
defaultThere is no formal contract monitoring process or continuous engagement with the supply chain, beyond the delivery of that particular service.
defaultIt is something that my organisation has been working on in terms of trying to develop things like outcomes frameworks or common sets of indicators, against which the performance of the supply chain can be monitored beyond the delivery of that service.
defaultOliver Henmandefault: I would add to what has been said.
default 
defaultIt is about generating efficiencies across the piece.
default 
defaultWe are not arguing that there should be more costly contracts; there are savings to be had across different budget lines.
defaultFor example, there is an organisation called Blue
default 
defaultSky
default 
defaultDevelopment and they work to employ ex
default-
defaultoffenders in maintenance and recycling contracts.
default 
defaultYou can actually quantify the saving for each of those people not reoffending, because we have calculated the cost of those prison places to be £41,000 per year.
default 
defaultIf those people are in meaningful employment, they are generating income and contributing to their society.
default 
defaultThere is a direct saving to the public purse; it is just across a number of budget lines.
defaultQ343 default&#xa0; 
defaultJohn Pugh:default Could I follow through on that example?
default 
defaultIt is possible, in a procurement exercise, to specify various things; it is impossible to specify others.
default 
defaultYou cannot specific local, but you can specify fresh, sustainable or something like that.
default 
defaultIn the case of prisoners, there is obviously added social value in dealing with ex
default-
defaultoffenders in that particular way.
default 
defaultIt is not a condition that you could write in to a contract, though, is it?
defaultOliver Henmandefault: The understanding we have is about how to develop good practice amongst contractors so that they are looking for those kinds of wider impacts.
default 
defaultIt comes back to the point about measurement and ensuring that when you go out to contract you can look at a wide range of different impacts, above and beyond the specific impact of the cost of that service.
defaultQ344 default&#xa0; 
defaultJohn Pugh:default Would it be possible to devise a contract where legitimately, under EU procurement rules, you would favour a contract that, say, did employ ex
default-
defaultoffenders, even though it might be slightly more expensive than one that did not?
defaultOliver Henmandefault: My understanding is that you would be able to favour social impact.
default 
defaultYou would not specify that it had to be ex
default-
defaultoffenders; you would not specify that it had to be a particular number of people; however, you could specify a social impact.
defaultIt is up to the provider to come up with a model that does actually make those savings.
default 
defaultProviders would look at across the piece.
default 
defaultIt may be ex
default-
defaultoffenders in this case; in another case it could be young people or other target groups.
defaultQ345 default&#xa0; 
defaultJohn Pugh:default Obviously, you looked at a whole range of procurement up and down the country.
default 
defaultHave you come across many instances of things going badly awry, where the contract is awarded and it is a blatant breach of EU procurement rules?
default 
defaultCan you think of examples?
defaultRicharddefault defaultMacfarlanedefault: Local authority legal officers and procurement officers are very careful.
defaultJohn Pugh:default That is what I was getting at.
default 
defaultIf people were working at the margins or not risk averse, you would get that.
defaultRicharddefault defaultMacfarlanedefault: People are out there being very cautious about this and they have to be convinced that there is a legal way of doing it.
default 
defaultYou have mentioned that you cannot mention local.
default 
defaultYou have to unpick that decision, going back to 1988.
default 
defaultThe EU procurement rules are in favour of social value in contracts.
default 
defaultWhat you have to do is specify it in a way that means a contractor from anywhere across 
defaultEurope
default has an equal chance of bidding.
default 
defaultThe way they typically do that around training and employment—this could relate to the ex
default-
defaultoffenders issue—is to say, “You must recruit eight ex
default-
defaultoffenders from this agency”.
default 
defaultThat is something that a contractor from 
defaultPoland
default, 
defaultDurham
default or 
defaultLondon
default can do.
defaultIf there is a tendency to disadvantage non
default-
defaultlocal contractors in that, you have to provide a source for those people.
default 
defaultYou might say, “You can recruit eight ex
default-
defaultoffenders from this agency in Brixton.”
default 
defaultThat levels the playing field.
default 
defaultBidders from anywhere in 
defaultEurope
default can go to that agency; the service is open to all of them; they know what they have to do; they can price that if they want to.
default 
defaultThat 
defaultdoes not contravene, in my knowledge and experience, the EC procurement directives, because you have kept a level playing field.
defaultQ346 default&#xa0; 
defaultJohn Pugh:default Taking a broad
default-
defaultbrush view, do you think the general effect of EU procurement regulations has been to act as a kind of deadener or does it incentivise councils to do things more variably?
defaultRicharddefault defaultMacfarlanedefault: There is a fear factor around it, particularly around the risk of challenge afterwards.
default 
defaultYou have to achieve quite a strong threshold of commitment and understanding before councils and their legal advisers are going to do this.
defaultQ347 default&#xa0; 
defaultJohn Pugh:default Let us quickly touch on the legal advisers.
default 
defaultLegal advisors, particularly on councils, in my experience, are generally cautious and trained a good while ago.
default 
defaultDo you think they are up to speed with revisions to EU regulations, or do you think they are trapped in the past?
defaultOliver Henmandefault: That is a very good point.
default 
defaultIt is about one of the things I mentioned before around awareness
default-
defaultraising and training for procurement officials and legal advisers.
default 
defaultThey often will think that the full scope of EU procurement rules applies in any contract, whereas, as you allude to, there are exceptions and thresholds under which you can be more flexible.
default 
defaultThat flexibility is not always used when it could be.
defaultMatthew Jackson:default It goes back to the culture of local
default 
defaultgovernment procurement officers.
default 
defaultWe effectively have two types of local
default 
defaultgovernment procurement people: those that are focused on transparency, compliance and risk management, and those that are focused on those three things, but, also, on the wider benefit that procurement can bring for a place, in terms of economic and social issues.
defaultJohn Pugh:default The ideal person has both features.
defaultMatthew Jackson:default Yes.
default 
defaultOn the question around training and skills development, procurement officers are taught a very particular trade around value for money, in its broadest sense, and price when it comes to procurement.
default 
defaultIf we are going to achieve wider social value through the procurement process, what we need is a more balanced set of skills within procurement teams, which reflects both that compliance with EU regulations but also the wider benefits that that process can bring.
defaultQ348 default&#xa0; 
defaultHeather Wheeler:default I am interested in whether you can give us some examples of where councils’ procurement systems and the culture of councils support local economies.
default 
defaultThe first question is this: do you think they do?
default 
defaultIf they do, could you give any examples where they are particularly loading social value into contracts?
default 
defaultIt would be very useful for the Committee to hear some specific examples that you have.
defaultMatthew Jackson:default It is dependent on the localities, to be honest.
default 
defaultWe have undertaken research with particular local authorities to try to understand where their spend is going and what impact it is having upon local economies, both at an individual level and also across 177 local authorities across the country.
default 
defaultThrough that research, what we have found is that, on average, local authorities will spend around 31% of their procurement spend with local businesses.
defaultWe have undertaken more specific and more individual bits of work, particularly with Manchester
default 
defaultCity
default 
defaultCouncil.
default 
defaultWe looked at their spend in 2008-09 to try to understand where £357
default 
defaultmillion of procurement money went.
default 
defaultWe found that 51.5% of that spend was within the 
defaultManchester
default local
default-
defaultauthority boundary, and the supply chain re
default-
defaultspent 25p in every pound they 
defaultreceived back in the 
defaultManchester
default economy.
default 
defaultWhat they have tried to do in 
defaultManchester
default is up the levels of local expenditure and influence the behaviour of the supply chain when it comes to wider benefits.
defaultOver the last three or four years, we have done a range of pieces of work with them.
default 
defaultWe have set up things like cross
default-
defaultdepartmental working groups where the priorities of different Departments across the authority are fed into the procurement process.
default 
defaultWe have set up suppliers’ networks, where we are trying organically to influence the behaviour of the supply chain, to think about the priorities of the authority.
default 
defaultWe have undertaken a range of work in areas of deprivation within the city, again with a focus on influencing the behaviour of the supply chain.
defaultA good example of that is in 
defaultArdwick
default, which is one of the most deprived neighbourhoods in the city, where there is £43
default 
defaultmillion of public investment from the local authority going directly into that community.
default 
defaultWhat we have tried to do is get suppliers based in that locality to think differently about how they procure and recruit, and about wider environmental concerns as well.
default 
defaultThe upshot of that work is that we have seen local expenditure increase from 51.5% in 2008
default–
default09 to around about 63% in 2012
default–
default13.
defaultThere is an impact there not only in networks and engagement activity with the supply chain, but also in terms of some of the wider engagement work the City
default 
defaultCouncil have done in terms of simplifying some of the bureaucracy associated with pre
default-
defaultqualification questionnaires and in terms of developing particular portals.
defaultFor me, the starting point for any procurement exercise is understanding impact and understanding where your spend goes at the moment, as a local authority, with a view to implementing a range of strategic activities to enhance local spend.
defaultOliver Henmandefault: I have a concrete example for you.
default 
defaultWithin the voluntary sector, as you know, many organisations do operate at the local level and do engage very much in local spending and creating local employment.
default 
defaultThey will work to attract new resources into an area from foundations and individual volunteers, and build social capital.
default 
defaultIn fact, 75% of our members indicate that they consider their area of benefit to be local, whatever exactly that “local area” might mean.
default 
defaultThe expenditure of all of those local organisations is about £25
default 
defaultbillion in total, if you were to join them together.
defaultThe concrete example, to come to that, is one in York City Council called Café West.
default 
defaultPrior to the tender, the local council engaged voluntary organisations to look at what would be the best way to work with local people.
default 
defaultThey then went out to a tender that works directly with people with disabilities and therefore creates employment pathways for those people.
default 
defaultIt uses local produce, so it supports the local economy; it invests in local suppliers and builds a wider local partnership through the actual space.
default 
defaultThe council then offered a six
default-
defaultmonth rent
default-
defaultfree contract at the start, and it was a won by United
default 
defaultResponse, which is a voluntary
default-
defaultsector provider.
default 
defaultIt was a good example of that whole chain being locally driven.
defaultRicharddefault defaultMacfarlanedefault: Could I give you an example from Birmingham City Council, 
defaultfrom 
defaultabout two and a half years ago?
default 
defaultThey adopted a procurement policy for jobs and skills, which was a mandatory policy across the whole of the council, for everything it procured.
default 
defaultThere were thresholds for the different sorts of services where that had to be applied.
default 
defaultThey changed the ethos from the employability team trying to persuade individual procurement teams they should include employment and training to those teams having an obligation and coming, therefore, to the training team and saying, “We have an obligation to do it; how do we do it?
default 
defaultWhat do we do?”
default 
defaultOn the back of that, they now have procurement and legal officers who are skilled and experienced at putting clauses into contracts.
defaultIt is going beyond new things.
default 
defaultYou will have heard that the Library of Birmingham had 360 trainee and apprenticeship jobs for people from 
defaultBirmingham
default.
default 
defaultIt has spread to Network
default 
defaultRail’s New
default 
defaultStreet
default 
defaultStation contracts.
default 
defaultThey are now doing it across all their contracts.
default 
defaultIt has gone into the 25
default-
defaultyear roads maintenance contract.
default 
defaultIt is in the Constructing West Midlands Framework contract.
default 
defaultThey are talking about it with social services with the Green New Deal contracts.
defaultIt is spreading out into services and way beyond construction.
default 
defaultIt is a market leader in taking across the council’s approach and saying, “Do this.
default 
defaultIf you do not want to do it, you have to make the argument why not.”
default 
defaultThat comes back to leadership and policy; it came from the leader of the council saying, “We are going to do this.”
default 
defaultThe first thing they did was set up a clear procurement policy, then get all of the procurement teams around the council in for training to understand that.
default 
defaultThat continues to work today.
default 
defaultThere are other examples, but that is a prime one.
defaultQ349 default&#xa0; 
defaultJohn Stevenson:default Richard, you started to touch on the next issue, which is skills and expertise, which, quite clearly, are significant matters for councils, council officers and, indeed, councillors.
default 
defaultCan I start with Matthew?
default 
defaultDo you think councils up and down the country actually have the staff with the abilities to deal with the complex world of modern
default-
defaultday procurement?
defaultMatthew Jackson:default It goes back to the point I started to touch on before.
default 
defaultIn terms of considerations around value for money and cost in its broadest senses, yes, the skills are there, but when it comes to wider benefit through procurement—i.e. the social
default-
defaultvalue issues we are talking about here today—the skills are not necessarily there.
default 
defaultTwo things need to happen to enable better skills within procurement teams.
default 
defaultOne is to recognise that procurement is a cycle.
default 
defaultIt goes from the commission stage and the design of services through to procurement strategy, pre
default-
defaultprocurement and delivery of the service.
default 
defaultThe social
default-
defaultvalue considerations need to come in a lot earlier.
default 
defaultIt is predominantly the role of the commissioners and the service designers to build in those social
default-
defaultvalue considerations.
defaultThe second thing is that procurement needs to become a much more cross
default-
defaultdepartmental activity.
default 
defaultWe need economic intelligence from economic
default 
defaultdevelopment and regeneration people feeding into the mindset and culture of procurement officers as well.
defaultThere is a need to re-stratify and realign the role of the procurement officer away from simply making a decision on the basis of cost and value for money, but also to be considerate of the wider economic and social challenges that a locality may face.
defaultQ350 default&#xa0; 
defaultJohn Stevenson:default On balance, you would say it is working in parts, but not in other parts.
defaultMatthew Jackson:default Yes.
defaultQ351 default&#xa0; 
defaultJohn Stevenson:default Richard, you mentioned one council that clearly does seem to be addressing the issue, but I am looking across the board.
default 
defaultWhat would be your impression?
defaultRicharddefault defaultMacfarlanedefault: My experience now, compared to 30 years ago, is that procurement officers are open to this, but they do not know how to do it.
default 
defaultThe first thing—a bit like we went through with John—is you have to present the argument to them in a logical way that overcomes their fears and concerns about European rules and so forth.
default 
defaultYou have to explain how to fit it in, and I have found them positive.
defaultThe second thing is that they need to network with new people.
default 
defaultFor example, around the routine procurement of care services, contract services or cleaning services, they work with officers that know about cleaning, construction or whatever it is.
default 
defaultWhatever social value you are looking at—it might be training; it might be small firms; it could be some other social value—they need to work with colleagues they have not worked with before.
defaultQ352 default&#xa0; 
defaultJohn Stevenson:default Are you suggesting collaborating with other authorities?
defaultRicharddefault defaultMacfarlanedefault: That could be one way of doing it.
default 
defaultThe danger of jointly purchasing is that contracts get bigger and bigger, and that becomes more difficult in another way for SMEs and small firms that traditionally provided services to bid.
default 
defaultLeaving that aside, yes, learning from others is quite important, as is the movement of procurement officers between authorities, carrying knowledge and experience with them.
defaultWhat I particularly had in mind was that a procurement officer needs to work with somebody who understands what the social-value requirement is.
default 
defaultIf that were, say, support for social enterprises, they would need to work with social
default-
defaultenterprise officers within the council or an external agency to understand what could go in the specification, what support there is out there to help contractors deliver it and how you would measure that.
default 
defaultIt is those practical, technical things around how you specify what you are trying to achieve in order to put it in the contract.
defaultAs Simon was saying, just let the thing roll.
default 
defaultAny contractor winning the contract has to deliver those outcomes.
defaultQ353 default&#xa0; 
defaultJohn Stevenson:default On that same subject, I would be interested in your response.
