defaultQ361 default&#xa0; 
defaultJames Morris:default I have one specific question about the community right to challenge, which is relevant to what you were just saying.
default 
defaultTo what extent are the existing procurement and commissioning processes that we have providing a disincentive to local voluntary—sector organisations for actually taking up the right to challenge?
default 
defaultIs that your experience?
defaultOliver Henmandefault: That is an interesting question.
default 
defaultIt certainly has not been as widely used as many people expected, yes.
default 
defaultWe have some evidence to show that only 22 rights to challenge were formally launched.
defaultJames Morris:default Is that 22 across the country?
defaultOliver Henmandefault: Yes.
default 
defaultAcross the country, only 22 have been through the process formally.
default 
defaultOf those, nine were rejected and two were accepted.
default 
defaultIt does seem to indicate, as you say, that there 
defaultis some limit to the ability to use that challenge, and that some councils are not feeling there is any obligation on them to respond to that challenge, because it does not necessarily fit within the standard procurement process.
defaultHowever, there is some evidence—it is harder to quantify—from members to say that the ability to refer to the right to challenge allows them to begin a conversation with the council that they would not otherwise have been able to begin.
default 
defaultAlthough we have only seen 22 actual formal processes, it may be the case that in other cases people are raising particular needs and the councils are responding less formally, rather than going through a full right to challenge.
default 
defaultThe evidence we have is that the right to challenge is sometimes seen as creating unnecessary confrontation.
default 
defaultActually, if things can be resolved less formally, sometimes they can be.
default 
defaultSometimes the particular need a community organisation has identified can be picked up in other ways.
default 
defaultIt is harder to quantify that, but we would certainly like to see more use of that opportunity for organisations to take on local services.
defaultMatthew Jackson:default From a local government perspective, local authorities are actively seeking to avoid going to challenge through trying to understand their market more effectively when it comes to the voluntary and community sector.
default 
defaultThey are implementing better engagement activities with the voluntary and community sector within their locality to avoid going through that exact challenge process.
defaultOne of the other challenges with the challenge is that it opens up the market a little bit.
default 
defaultIf you are highlighting that you want to deliver a library service, for example, you are opening yourself up to a full tender exercise that often involves large private
default-
defaultsector organisations engaging in that process.
default 
defaultYou will not necessarily have any winners, if you like, in the voluntary and community sector by challenging the provision of those services.
default 
defaultIt is more effective to have a relationship between the local
default-
defaultauthority commissioning people and the voluntary and community sector in place to enable better outcomes.
