defaultQ371 default&#xa0; 
defaultJames Morris:default I was talking to a company in my constituency the other day who were complaining about the local authority procurement process.
default 
defaultThey had received four identical documents in the course of this tendering process and they calculated that it had reached the point where they had spent so much money on conforming to the requirements that had come out of this particular local authority that it now meant it was not profitable for them to continue with it.
default 
defaultHow common is it in local government that, because of this risk aversion you were talking about, we end up in a situation where totally valid small and medium
default-
defaultsized businesses make the judgement it is not worth them pursuing a tender because of the onerous compliance requirements that are placed upon them?
defaultMartin defaultMcTaguedefault: It is very common.
default 
defaultIt is one of the biggest factors that came out of our research.
default 
defaultIt is driven by risk aversion.
default 
defaultIt is driven by the idea that if you stack an enormous PQQ at the beginning of the process you will somehow insulate yourself from risk.
default 
defaultThere is the opposite reaction of, “You should get rid of PQQs”.
default 
defaultHowever, the tender would then become infinitely more complex and difficult.
default 
defaultIn the end, it comes back to John’s point earlier: it is about leadership.
default 
defaultIt is about saying, “We see a bigger picture here—not just shaving a few pennies off the price of your paperclips.
default 
defaultWe want to show leadership and show some commitment to smaller businesses.”
defaultAlundefault defaultRafiquedefault: It is also that you should just apply an appropriate level of competition.
default 
defaultWe find that a lot of tenders these days are very onerous and they do not have to be.
default 
defaultIt is surprisingly common.
default 
defaultYou can reduce the tender depending on the size of the opportunity.
default 
defaultThat is where the public sector needs some guidance in terms of what is acceptable for that.
defaultDr defaultTellesdefault:default One of the things we have done in 
defaultBangor
default is take on exactly that problem and tackle it head on.
default 
defaultAt Bangor
default 
defaultUniversity, we are of the opinion that low
default-
defaultvalue contracts should be advertised.
default 
defaultThey should not only be awarded via request for quotes, whereby only two, three or five companies are invited.
default 
defaultEveryone should have an opportunity to bid for that contract.
default 
defaultWhat we do not agree is that for a £10,000 or £20,000 contract the level of detail and information required should be identical to that which is required for a £100,000, £200,000 or £2 million contract.
default 
defaultIt does not make sense.
defaultWhat we have done is gone back to the drawing board and designed from scratch what we call a simplified open procedure, whereby we are able to award contracts in less than 40 days from start to finish.
default 
defaultWe eliminated everything that was unnecessary; the selection stage, the PQQ, was gone.
default 
defaultObviously, we require self-declaration, as it is going to be mandatory from 2016, when the new directives come in.
default 
defaultWe require a self-declaration saying, “Yes, we have the insurance levels.
default 
defaultYes, we have the policies you require.”
defaultAt the end of the day, what we want to identify is the best bid, not the best bidder.
default 
defaultWhat tends to happen with PQQs, which is why they are so long and drawn-out, is PQQs are used to identify the best bidder, which—unfortunately, because we are all biased—means people are going to look at the bid influenced by the decisions that have been taken at the selection stage and say, “This company was the best bidder; why do they not have the best bid?
default 
defaultPerhaps we can skew the results a little bit and change the numbers.”
defaultI do not think this has happened in practice, but I know that in 
defaultPortugal
default and 
defaultSpain
default people who are involved in selecting bidders at the start cannot be involved in selecting the bids at the end and making a final decision.
default 
defaultThe reason for that is precisely to avoid the bias.
default 
defaultI see that every day when I am marking my students’ exams.
default 
defaultFor example, I am not authorised or entitled to know which student’s script I have in front of me.
default 
defaultI need to evaluate the exam on the merits of what is written and not on the merits of the candidate, who I may know.
default 
defaultIt is the same thing with procurement.
default 
defaultYou are supposed to identify and award the contract to the best bid, not the best bidder.
defaultBasically, what we have done at Bangor was to reduce the timescales, remove what was not necessary, simplify the procedure, use e
default-
defaultprocurement, obviously, do everything online and, for example, impose word limits, which is a very sensible thing to do.
default 
defaultAt least this is what we do with the essays of our students.
defaultSo far, the pilots we have done in two councils, Carmarthenshire
default 
defaultCounty
default 
defaultCouncil and Gwynedd
default 
defaultCouncil, have been very successful.
default 
defaultIt can be done.
default 
defaultThere is nothing in the law to say that it cannot be done.
