defaultHeather Wheeler:default You have answered my question about how councils are not doing enough to minimise procurement costs for you.
default 
defaultI would ask this next question, wouldn’t I?
default 
defaultHow much of the bureaucracy in local
default 
defaultgovernment procurement is due to local authorities and how much is due to EU regulation?
defaultDr defaultTellesdefault:default I will take that one.
default 
defaultEU regulations are a very convenient scapegoat in these matters.
default 
defaultAs I have highlighted, only 25% of contracts are actually covered by EU rules.
default 
defaultBelow that, you can do pretty much what you want.
default 
defaultI do not know why it is not different for the other 75% of contracts, but it is not a problem with EU law.
default 
defaultIt is a problem at either the local, regional or central levels of government.
defaultWhat is happening with procurement is a certain feeling that you have to go for the gold
default-
defaultplated option.
default 
defaultIf you go for the restricted procedure and you go for the PQQ, if you select the IBMs and 
defaultAccentures
default of the world you are basically protecting yourself down the line.
default 
defaultThe interesting bit is that, when you go and see what happens after the contracts get awarded, the number of legal challenges here in the 
defaultUK
default is shockingly small.
defaultAs far as I know—this is data supplied to me by a colleague of mine, Dr
default 
defaultRichard
default 
defaultCraven, from the 
defaultUniversity
default of 
defaultNorthumbria
default—we had less than 25 judgments on public procurement in 2012 and around 20 or 
default25 in
default 2011.
default 
defaultThe numbers are even lower for previous years.
default 
defaultWhat that tells me is that, on the one hand, people who do procurement exercises are being very careful, but they are being very careful without actually needing to do so.
default 
defaultThere are usually no legal consequences of trying to push the practice a little bit more.
default 
defaultIf you have 10,000 procurement exercises above the EU thresholds and you only have 25 challenges, the risk that the procurement procedure you are running is going to be challenged is very low.
defaultThere is a lot that can be done at the process level, which should be done.
default 
defaultAs I say, for the contracts below the EU thresholds, they should be done from the ground up.
default 
defaultIf you do them from the ground up, instead of taking the current open procedure and trying to remove things from it, which is what the Government has decided to do over the last couple of years, you should start with a whiteboard and a blank sheet of paper.
default 
defaultThat way, you will be able to have a much leaner and much more streamlined process and procedure, which is suitable and suited for small companies.
default 
defaultAt the end of the day, that is what you want.
default 
defaultYou want to save time; you want to save money; you want to reduce the costs for the procurer and the suppliers.
default 
defaultThat is what you should be doing.
default 
defaultOnce you find that way of simplifying the open procedure—in 
defaultBangor
default, we have done some work in that area—it should be mandatory for everyone to follow.
defaultIt is not the fault of EU law that there is no centralisation below the threshold and every authority does what they want to do.
defaultQ381 default&#xa0; 
defaultHeather Wheeler:default I know you are desperate to get in but we are really quite late for time.
default 
defaultI will move on, if you do not mind.
default 
defaultI have another difficult question: how can councils ensure that small suppliers are not disadvantaged by large contractors failing to pay them promptly?
defaultMartin defaultMcTaguedefault: That is the point I made earlier, and it is a really important point.
default 
defaultIt is relatively easy for them to solve: they can introduce that clause in their contracts to their prime suppliers.
defaultQ382 default&#xa0; 
defaultHeather Wheeler:default How do they monitor it?
defaultMartin defaultMcTaguedefault: There are all sorts of ways they can monitor it.
default 
defaultI can give you examples.
default 
defaultI will write to you afterwards about how we have seen certain councils apply this very successfully.
default 
defaultThere are a whole variety of ways in which they can do it.
default 
defaultHowever, they set the benchmark very early on.
default 
defaultThey make it clear to their prime suppliers that they are watching them.
default 
defaultThe prime suppliers do not want to lose their relationship.
default 
defaultYou may need a bit of an audit trail afterwards to check this, but it needs that leadership from the council to say that they want them to pass those payment terms on.
defaultQ383 default&#xa0; 
defaultHeather Wheeler:default This is my last question; it is really for Dr
default 
defaultTelles
default.
default 
defaultIn respect of the pilots for simplifying low
default-
defaultvalue tender processes, how scalable are the lessons we can learn from that?
default 
defaultIs it possible to really copy that across the whole country?
defaultDr defaultTellesdefault:default I would say yes.
default 
defaultWe ran eight or nine pilots with Carmarthenshire
default 
defaultCounty
default 
defaultCouncil and Gwynedd
default 
defaultCouncil.
default 
defaultEveryone was happy with them—both procurers and the private sector.
default 
defaultWe had no complaints from either the private sector or the public sector.
default 
defaultPeople were really happy with it because, especially for the lead officers that were being involved in the process, it demystified procurement a lot; it does not need to be as complex as it is made to be.
defaultThat is an important lesson for us as well.
default 
defaultIf that happens in small councils, it is going to be valid in big councils.
default 
defaultIf you start applying a methodology like the one developed there and roll it out across the country, yes, there will be some teething pains.
default 
defaultWe have already identified quite a few issues that can be solved, but, at the end of the day, everyone will benefit from it.
default 
defaultNeither the procurers nor the suppliers are going to get everything they would want from that process; that is not the objective.
default 
defaultThe objective is to find something that is a middle ground that works well for everyone.
default 
defaultIt is pretty much scalable for low
default-
defaultvalue contracts below the EU threshold anywhere in the 
defaultUK
default.
defaultAlundefault defaultRafiquedefault: To the other point about whether it is the local authorities or the EU regulations, to give you an example, with Mole
default 
defaultValley
default 
defaultCouncil we developed a procurement system to help them procure more effectively and adopt from a buyer and a supplier side, but we were told by them we would have more chance of changing our system than they would of changing their procedures for local
default 
defaultgovernment procurement.
defaultYou asked about which one it is.
default 
defaultThey had actually interpreted the full OJEU procedures for small
default-
defaultvalue tenders, so, in fact, in some ways it is not only the local authorities or the EU regulations; it is both together.
default 
defaultObviously, if we did that and incorporated it all within our systems, it would just exacerbate the issue.
default 
defaultAll of the local councils would then use our system and create just as many problems.
default 
defaultI just wanted to add that point there.
defaultQ384 default&#xa0; 
defaultChris Williamson:default Mr
default 
defaultRafique
default, you touched on this in your final answer.
default 
defaultWhen people talk about whether or not it is EU procurement regulations that are the problem, I am left asking why it is that EU procurement issues are not a problem for our colleagues on the continent.
default 
defaultIs it out interpretation?
defaultAlundefault defaultRafiquedefault: Yes, absolutely.
default 
defaultIt is our interpretation.
defaultQ385 default&#xa0; 
defaultChris Williamson:default Does that come back to training?
default 
defaultWhat do we do about that?
defaultAlundefault defaultRafiquedefault: To give you an example, there are lots of different scoring mechanisms for weighted tenders.
default 
defaultThey are not really set out in OJEU, but we interpret them in a lot of different ways.
default 
defaultOnce someone has interpreted them, they are copied.
default 
defaultWhen you have this interpretation that is very long-winded and may be incorrect and inappropriate, it is then copied throughout the 
defaultcouncils and this proliferates the issue.
default 
defaultYou need someone to step in and answer the question and say, “That is not correct”.
defaultChris Williamson:default Who is that someone?
default 
defaultThat is like saying, “They should do something about this”.
default 
defaultWho is it?
defaultAlundefault defaultRafiquedefault: You could have some regional centres of excellence or someone they could speak to.
default 
defaultIt could either be that or you would have to go around and train everyone again.
default 
defaultYou are quite right: for low
default-
defaultvalue procurement, the problem is the interpretation of the rule.
default 
defaultSome people take the full OJEU process and interpret it for the low
default-
defaultvalue tenders, and put too much rigour towards it.
defaultMartin defaultMcTaguedefault: In part, the EU is an easy scapegoat, is it not?
default 
defaultIf you really do not want to do something, blame the EU and pretty much anybody will accept it.
